prompt:
Add an `android` dev shell to `flake.nix` that provides the JDK + Android SDK + gradle needed to build the Capacitor APK locally via `nix develop .#android`, mirroring what the GH Actions `build-android` job in `.github/workflows/test.yml` does (setup-java + setup-android).

**Background ŌĆö what flux needs:**
- Capacitor 6.x wrapper under `android/`, appId `dev.gunk.flux`
- `android/variables.gradle`: `minSdkVersion = 22`, `compileSdkVersion = 34`, `targetSdkVersion = 34`
- `android/build.gradle`: Android Gradle Plugin `8.2.1`
- `android/gradle/wrapper/gradle-wrapper.properties`: gradle `8.2.1` (the wrapper downloads its own gradle, so we only strictly need a JDK to run `./gradlew` ŌĆö but include `pkgs.gradle` in the shell for convenience when running raw gradle commands during exploration)

**Existing flake structure (read it first):**
- `devShells.default` has `nodejs_20`, `nixfmt-rfc-style`, `klaus`
- `devShells.test` has `nodejs_20`, `playwright-driver.browsers` with a shellHook that sets `PLAYWRIGHT_BROWSERS_PATH` and pre-installs npm deps
- `pkgs = nixpkgs.legacyPackages.${system};` (vanilla, no config overrides)

**What to add ŌĆö a NEW `devShells.android`** (do NOT extend `devShells.default` ŌĆö Android SDK is multi-GB and most flux dev is web; keeping it separate matches the pattern set by `devShells.test`):

```nix
devShells.android = let
  androidPkgs = import nixpkgs {
    inherit system;
    config = {
      allowUnfree = true;
      android_sdk.accept_license = true;
    };
  };
  androidComposition = androidPkgs.androidenv.composeAndroidPackages {
    platformVersions = [ "34" ];
    buildToolsVersions = [ "34.0.0" ];
    includeNDK = false;
    # platformTools is included by default
  };
  androidSdk = androidComposition.androidsdk;
in androidPkgs.mkShell {
  buildInputs = with androidPkgs; [
    nodejs_20
    jdk17
    gradle
    androidSdk
  ];

  ANDROID_HOME = "${androidSdk}/libexec/android-sdk";
  ANDROID_SDK_ROOT = "${androidSdk}/libexec/android-sdk";
  # AGP 8.x needs aapt2 from build-tools; point gradle at the nix-provided one
  # so it doesn't try to download its own.
  GRADLE_OPTS = "-Dorg.gradle.project.android.aapt2FromMavenOverride=${androidSdk}/libexec/android-sdk/build-tools/34.0.0/aapt2";

  shellHook = ''
    echo "Flux android dev shell"
    echo "  ANDROID_HOME=$ANDROID_HOME"
    echo ""
    echo "Commands:"
    echo "  npm ci && npm run build && npx cap sync android   - sync web bundle into android/"
    echo "  (cd android && ./gradlew assembleDebug)            - build debug APK"
    echo "  (cd android && ./gradlew tasks)                    - list gradle tasks"
  '';
};
```

Notes for you (the implementing agent):
- The `import nixpkgs { ... }` with `config` is necessary because `androidenv` pulls unfree, license-restricted SDK components. Don't try to apply this config to the top-level `pkgs` binding ŌĆö it would force every consumer of the default/test shells to also accept the Android license. Keep the configured import scoped to `devShells.android`.
- `includeNDK = false` ŌĆö Capacitor doesn't need NDK; keep the download small (it's already huge).
- Confirm exact attribute paths (`androidComposition.androidsdk` vs `.platform-tools` etc) by reading the androidenv docs in nixpkgs if you're unsure: `nix-instantiate --eval -E 'with import <nixpkgs> { config.android_sdk.accept_license = true; config.allowUnfree = true; }; builtins.attrNames (androidenv.composeAndroidPackages { platformVersions = ["34"]; buildToolsVersions = ["34.0.0"]; })'`.

**Validation (run all three before opening PR):**

1. `nix run nixpkgs#nixfmt -- --check .` ŌĆö passes (existing `nix-lint` CI job will check this)
2. `nix flake check --all-systems` ŌĆö passes (this will evaluate but NOT build the android shell on non-x86_64-linux systems, which is fine)
3. **End-to-end build inside the shell:**
   ```
   nix develop .#android --command bash -c '
     set -e
     npm ci
     npm run build
     npx cap sync android
     cd android
     ./gradlew assembleDebug --no-daemon
     ls -la app/build/outputs/apk/debug/app-debug.apk
   '
   ```
   This will be slow on first run (multi-GB SDK download from the nix cache, plus gradle bootstrapping). If the cache doesn't have the SDK derivation it'll build from upstream ŌĆö that's expected. The APK should land at `android/app/build/outputs/apk/debug/app-debug.apk`.

**Update `README.md`:** add a section under whatever existing dev-setup section there is (look for `nix develop` references) mentioning `nix develop .#android` for android work, with the same three-step command sequence (npm ci ŌåÆ npm run build && npx cap sync ŌåÆ ./gradlew assembleDebug).

**Out of scope (do NOT touch):**
- `.github/workflows/test.yml` ŌĆö leave the CI job using setup-java + setup-android. The dev-shell is for local use only. (Switching CI to nix is a separate decision; the Android SDK in CI's nix cache would be slow without proper caching.)
